  "prompt": "Though people tell me I am pretty, why do I sometimes feel not pretty or I don't like what I see in the mirror?",
  "response": "There can be several reasons why you might feel this way:\n\n1. Psychological factors\n- Low self-esteem\n- Negative self-perception\n- Comparison with unrealistic beauty standards\n- Past experiences or criticism\n- Inner self-critic\n\n2. Mental health influences\n- Anxiety\n- Depression\n- Body dysmorphia\n- Negative thought patterns\n\n3. External influences\n- Social media and unrealistic beauty standards\n- Constant exposure to edited/filtered images\n- Peer or societal pressure\n- Cultural beauty expectations\n\n4. Personal perception\n- Familiarity with your own appearance\n- Focusing on perceived flaws\n- Emotional state affecting self-image\n\n5. Biological factors\n- Hormonal changes\n- Stress\n- Fatigue\n- Physical health\n\nSuggestions:\n- Practice self-compassion\n- Challenge negative thoughts\n- Focus on positive attributes\n- Seek professional help if feelings persist\n- Practice self-care\n- Develop a healthy self-image\n- Surround yourself with supportive people\n\nRemember, beauty is subjective and goes beyond physical appearance. Your worth isn't determined by how you look, but by your character, talents, and how you treat others.\n\nWould you like to discuss this further?",
